<p><em><strong>Mark Berry,</strong> Acting CEO of Phoenix Rising, presents the Board of Directors’ open letter to Queen Mary University of London (QMUL) urging them to release the PACE trial data, and hopes that other non-UK organisations will join British charities in the same request&#8230; </em></p>
<p><em><a href="http://phoenixrising.me/archives/27969/me-cfs-pace-data" rel="attachment wp-att-28037"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-28037" src="http://phoenixrising.me/wp-content/uploads/ME-CFS-PACE-data.jpg" alt="ME-CFS-PACE-data" width="353" height="298" /></a></em>On 1 February, ME/CFS patient Clark Ellis wrote an <a href="https://autodidactauthor.wordpress.com/2016/02/01/pace-trials-forbidden-fruit-part-3-charities-must-echo-patient-calls-for-data-release/" target="_blank">open letter</a> to seven major British ME/CFS charities to ask them to contact QMUL.</p>
<p>He wanted them to write their own open letters to request QMUL to abandon its appeal against the Information Commissioner’s decision that it must release PACE trial data to a patient who had requested it for independent analysis.&hellip; <a href="http://phoenixrising.me/archives/27969" class="read-more">Read More</a></p>
